SIMPLE: sepulchral
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Sepulchral
<hw>Se*pul"chral</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[L.
<ets>sepulcralis</ets>: cf. F. <ets>s⟦eacute⟧pulcral</ets>.]</ety>
<sn>1.</sn> <def>Of or pertaining to burial, to the grave, or to
monuments erected to the memory of the dead; <as>as, a
<ex>sepulchral</ex> stone; a <ex>sepulchral</ex>
inscription.</as></def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Unnaturally low and grave; hollow in tone; -- said
of sound, especially of the voice.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>This exaggerated dulling of the voice . . . giving what is
commonly called a <qex>sepulchral</qex> tone.</q> <rj><qau>H.
Sweet.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Sepulture</ent>⟦br⟧
